  <dsc><c01 id="aspace_ref12_hd5" level="series"><did><unittitle>Correspondence</unittitle><unitid>I.</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1827/1915" type="inclusive">1827-1915</unitdate></did><scopecontent id="aspace_e01c9e84370a9edb8ff38b888306fa95"><head>Scope and Content Notes</head><p>The earliest correspondence in the collection relates to William's father David Knox. These letters, dating from 1827 to 1833, are mainly from his first wife Sarah Knox and her family. The bulk of the collection is contained within the first series, which primarily houses the William Knox correspondence. The letters begin when William left home in 1849 to attend Allegheny College in Meadville, Pennsylvania. The letters during this period, which are mostly from his father and younger siblings, contain news about family members as well as the residents of Brownsville, Pennsylvania. As the years progress, the content of the correspondence shifts to more serious concerns, such as the Civil War draft and the early deaths of several of William's children. This series contains a number of letters addressed to William's wife, Elizabeth, from members of her family.</p></scopecontent><c02 id="aspace_ref13_4rq" level="file"><did><unittitle>Correspondence</unittitle><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1827/1834" type="inclusive">1827-1834</unitdate><container id="aspace_6cc43ec07a1589bb41660bf91ac4df8c" label="Mixed Materials" type="box">1</container><container id="aspace_bd73a955f4f2328d0c88690b2df877f3" parent="aspace_6cc43ec07a1589bb41660bf91ac4df8c" type="folder">1</container><dao xlink:actuate="onRequest" xlink:href="31735070000462" xlink:show="new" xlink:title="William F. Knox Correspondence" xlink:type="simple"><daodesc><p>William F. Knox Correspondence: 1827-1834</p></daodesc></dao></did></c02><c02 id="aspace_ref14_p7a" level="file"><did><unittitle>Correspondence</unittitle><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1845/1849" type="inclusive">1845-1849</unitdate><container id="